HEADWORD: Glaive
<hw>Glaive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>glaive</ets>,
L. <ets>gladius</ets>; prob. akin to E. <ets>claymore</ets>. Cf.
<er>Gladiator</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A weapon formerly used,
consisting of a large blade fixed on the end of a pole, whose edge was
on the outside curve; also, a light lance with a long sharp-pointed
head.</def> <rj><au>Wilhelm.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A sword; -- used poetically and loosely.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>glaive</qex> which he did wield.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glama</ent>⟦br⟧
